<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: COUNTYWIDE; ARCHBISHOP TO BLESS NEW CHURCH IN IRVINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THAO HUA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A controversial Greek Orthodox church, deemed an eyesore by some residents 
when it was built more than two years ago, will be officially blessed Sunday by 
the denomination's leader in the Americas. 
</P>
<P>
 Archbishop Iakovos arrives in Orange County today for a weekend of activities 
highlighted by the consecration of St. Paul's Greek Orthodox Church on Alton 
Parkway in Irvine at 9:30 a.m. Bishop Anthony, bishop of the western United 
States, also will attend. 
</P>
<P>
 "To come this far, the feeling is just awesome," said the Rev. Father George 
Stephanides, the church's priest, "especially considering what we've been 
through in the last few years." 
</P>
<P>
 Protests from the community dogged the church even before it was built. In 
1991, residents of the Bloomdale cul-de-sac protested construction of the 
$6-million edifice, saying the Byzantine-style structure was out of place amid 
their homes. They also contended the 70-foot copper dome obscured their view of 
the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
 "With all the controversy, we gave in 10 feet," Stephanides said. 
</P>
<P>
 The church opened its doors to parishioners in May, 1992, but the consecration 
was delayed until the interior could be completed.THAO HUA 
</P>
</TEXT>
